Path: godot/tutorials/audio/audio_effects.rst
Summary: This section describes the available equalizer nodes in Godot.
EQ6, EQ10, EQ21
Godot provides three equalizers with different numbers of bands, which are represented in the title (6, 10, and 21 bands, respectively).
---CHUNK---
Document: Audio Effects Tutorial
Path: godot/tutorials/audio/audio_effects.rst
Summary: Explains the concept of audio filters in Godot, their purpose, and the base Filter class.
Filter
A "filter" controls the gain of frequencies, through the use of a *cutoff* as a frequency threshold. It differs from an equalizer in that it uses different "shapes" to control frequencies; meaning frequencies will have their gain adjusted whether they are lower, higher, at, or outside the cutoff point, depending on the filter type. Filters can help give room to each sound and create interesting effects.
Note: This audio effect is what all other filters inherit from. It should not be used directly.
---CHUNK---
Document: Audio Effects Tutorial
Path: godot/tutorials/audio/audio_effects.rst
Summary: Explains the HardLimiter audio effect and its use case for preventing clipping.
HardLimiter
A "limiter" disallows audio signals from exceeding a given volume threshold level. Hard limiters predict volume peaks, and will smoothly apply gain reduction when the volume crosses the ceiling threshold level. It works similarly to a compressor, but is designed to not let the volume cross a certain volume level at all. Adding a limiter as the last effect of the Master bus is good practice, as it offers an easy safeguard against clipping. If clipping is desired, consider using the distortion effect on clip mode.
---CHUNK---
Document: HighPassFilter
Path: godot/tutorials/audio/audio_effects.rst
Summary: Describes the HighPassFilter audio effect, explaining its function and use case.
HighPassFilter
A "high-pass" filter attenuates frequencies lower than the cutoff point and allows higher frequencies to pass unchanged. This filter can be used to remove the bass content of a signal, making it sound "thinner".
---CHUNK---
Document: Audio Effects
Path: godot/tutorials/audio/audio_effects.rst
Summary: Describes the HighShelfFilter audio effect.
HighShelfFilter
A "high-shelf" filter controls the gain of all frequencies above the cutoff point. This filter can be used to increase or decrease clarity of a sound.
---CHUNK---
Document: Audio Effects
Path: godot/tutorials/audio/audio_effects.rst
Summary: Describes the deprecated Limiter audio effect and provides a usage example.
Note: This is the old limiter effect, and it is recommended to use the new hard limiter effect instead. This effect is kept to preserve compatibility, however it should be considered deprecated.
Here is an example of how this effect works: if the ceiling is set to -12 dB, and the threshold is 0 dB, all samples going through get reduced by 12 dB. This changes the waveform of the sound and introduces distortion.
---CHUNK---
Document: Audio Effects Tutorial
Path: godot/tutorials/audio/audio_effects.rst
Summary: Describes the LowPassFilter audio effect in Godot.
LowPassFilter
A "low-pass" filter attenuates frequencies higher than the cutoff point and allows lower frequencies to pass unchanged. Low pass filters can be used to simulate "muffled" sounds. For instance, underwater sounds, sounds blocked by walls, or distant sounds.
---CHUNK---
Document: Audio Effects Tutorial
Path: godot/tutorials/audio/audio_effects.rst
Summary: Describes the LowShelfFilter audio effect and its purpose.
LowShelfFilter
A "low-shelf" filter controls the gain of all frequencies below the cutoff point. This filter can be used to adjust the "strength" of a sound, by increasing or decreasing the gain of the bass range.
---CHUNK---
Document: Audio Effects
Path: godot/tutorials/audio/audio_effects.rst
Summary: Describes the NotchFilter audio effect, its function, and use cases.

NotchFilter
A "notch" filter attenuates the frequencies at the cutoff point, and allows frequencies outside of that point to pass unchanged. It is the opposite of the band-pass filter. This filter can be used to give more room for other sounds to play at the cutoff point. Because of how much it attenuates frequencies, it can also be used to completely remove very specific and undesired frequencies.
---CHUNK---
Document: Audio Effects Tutorial
Path: godot/tutorials/audio/audio_effects.rst
Summary: Describes the Panner audio effect and its use case.
Panner
Moves the sound to the left or right. Headphones are recommended when configuring this effect.
Note: This effect may not be necessary with AudioStreamPlayer2D and AudioStreamPlayer3D, since they handle panning automatically.
---CHUNK---
Document: Audio Effects
Path: godot/tutorials/audio/audio_effects.rst
Summary: Describes the Phaser audio effect in Godot.
Phaser
A "phaser" effect creates a copy that is out-of-phase and mixes back together with the original. The copy is then modulated by an LFO (low-frequency oscillator), which makes some frequencies cancel each other out in interesting ways. The result of that is a series of peaks and troughs that sweep across the spectrum. This effect can be used to create sci-fi effects or Darth Vader-like voices.
---CHUNK---
Document: Audio Effects Tutorial
Path: godot/tutorials/audio/audio_effects.rst
Summary: Describes the PitchShift audio effect in Godot.
PitchShift
Allows the adjustment of the signal's pitch independently of its speed. All frequencies can be raised or lowered with minimal effect on transients. This effect can be useful to create unusually high or deep voices. Note that altering pitch can sound unnatural when pushed outside of a narrow window.
---CHUNK---
Document: Audio Effects Tutorial
Path: godot/tutorials/audio/audio_effects.rst
Summary: Describes the Record audio effect for storing audio data into an AudioStreamWAV.
Record
Stores audio data into an AudioStreamWAV. One usage example of this effect is to record microphone input and save as a WAV file.
---CHUNK---
Document: Audio Effects Tutorial
Path: godot/tutorials/audio/audio_effects.rst
Summary: This section describes the Reverb audio effect and its use in Godot.
Reverb is an audio effect that plays back a decaying copy of the input audio, creating a blurry echo or reverberation. It is useful for simulating sounds in various spaces, from small rooms to large caverns. Reverb is similar to the delay effect but produces a less distinct sound. Combining reverb with delay can create natural-sounding environments. Reverb is often implemented using Area3Ds and reverb buses.
---CHUNK---
Document: Audio Effects
Path: godot/tutorials/audio/audio_effects.rst
Summary: Describes the SpectrumAnalyzer audio effect for visualizing audio amplitude across frequency ranges.
SpectrumAnalyzer plots the amplitude of the audio signal within specified frequency ranges. This would typically be used for real-time audio visualization, like a spectrogram. Visualizing voices can be a great way to draw attention to them without increasing their volume. This effect does not alter audio. Note: Accessing AudioEffectSpectrumAnalyzerInstance is necessary to make use of this effect. A demo project using this can be found here.
---CHUNK---
Document: Audio Effects
Path: godot/tutorials/audio/audio_effects.rst
Summary: Describes the StereoEnhance audio effect for widening or narrowing sound.
StereoEnhance adjusts the gain of the left and right channels and can make mono sounds stereo through phase shift. This effect can be used to widen or narrow a sound. Headphones are recommended when configuring this effect.